{"type":"message","id":"60b74c6b","parentId":"1fcedcb4","timestamp":"2026-04-04T17:06:32.372Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Perfect! I can see the existing cron jobs. The group good morning is at `0 8 * * *` (8 AM IST daily) with id `145272a0-f193-4723-94f5-38dada60c1f0`. It sends to `-1003606834639` (the Nrexya group).\n\nFor April 27th specifically, I need to create a one-time cron job that runs at 8 AM IST on that date. The schedule would be:\n- kind: \"cron\" \n- expr: \"0 8 27 4 *\" (April 27th at 8:00)\n- tz: \"Asia/Kolkata\"\n\nOr I could use \"at\" with a specific timestamp. Let's think about the date: April 27, 2026. What day of week is that? I need to figure out the cron expression. April 27, 2026... Let me calculate. 2026-04-27. I can check what day that is, but it doesn't matter for cron. The cron expression `0 8 27 4 *` means minute 0, hour 8, day-of-month 27, month 4 (April), any day-of-week. That's correct.\n\nAlternatively, I could use the \"at\" kind with an ISO timestamp. But cron is simpler.\n\nThe payload should be similar to the existing good morning job but maybe with a message that references the exam. But the user said \"normal 8 am\" so I think they just want the regular good morning message, but specifically on April 27th.\n\nLet me create the job:\n- name: \"good-morning-april27\" or something\n- schedule: cron with expr \"0 8 27 4 *\" and tz \"Asia/Kolkata\"\n- sessionTarget: \"isolated\"\n- payload: same kind \"agentTurn\" with similar message but maybe modified to be exam-themed?\n- delivery: same as group good morning, to -1003606834639\n\nWait, the user said \"normal 8 am\" — they might want the normal good morning message but just on that date. So I should probably use the same message template, but maybe I should customize it to mention the exam? The original request from \".\" was \"I want a msg telling to me about april 27th exam.\" But then Nemesis said \"remind with the good morning mssg on 27th\" and then later \".\" said \"Yeah this is best\". So I think they want a special good morning message on April 27th that mentions the exam.\n\nBut then Nemesis said \"normal 8 am\" which could mean: just the normal good morning (not special), at 8 AM. But the original intent was to remind about the exam. So I should probably include the exam reminder in the good morning message.\n\nI'll create a special good morning message for April 27th that includes a note about the exam. I'll use a similar structure to the daily good morning but add an exam reminder.\n\nLet me craft the message: \"Good morning, Nrexya! 🌅\\n\\nToday is April 27th — don't forget about your exam! You've got this 💪\\n\\nHave a great Saturday! 🖤\"\n\nActually, I should follow the pattern of the existing good morning job: it uses a placeholder {{question}}. In the current job, the message is: \"🌅 Good morning, Nrexya! \\n\\n{{question}}\\n\\nHave a great Saturday! 🖤\". The agent creates the question. So I could either replicate that or send a fixed message.\n\nSimplest: create a one-time job that sends a fixed message about the exam. But the existing job uses an agent to generate a custom question each day. For a one-off, maybe just send a fixed message is fine.\n\nLet me decide: I'll create a cron job that uses agentTurn with a simple message that includes both the good morning vibe and the exam reminder. I can either:\n1. Use the same agent message but with a custom instruction to include exam reminder\n2. Use a simpler direct message send\n\nLooking at the jobs, they all use agentTurn and then the agent uses the message tool to send. So I'll follow that pattern. I'll craft a message that says something like:\n\n\"Read CRON-CONTEXT.md. Get today date. Create a warm good morning message for Nrexya group that also includes a reminder about the April 27th exam. Use message(action=send, channel=telegram, target=-1003606834639, message=...)\"\n\nBut that might be overkill for a one-time job. I could just have the job send a direct message without an agent? The payload requires either systemEvent or agentTurn. systemEvent injects into main session; agentTurn spawns an isolated agent.\n\nThe current good morning jobs use agentTurn. That seems to be the pattern. I'll follow the same pattern.\n\nLet me check what a typical payload looks like:\n\nFor group good morning (id 145272a0...):\n\"payload\": {\n  \"kind\": \"agentTurn\",\n  \"message\": \"Read /root/.openclaw/workspace/CRON-CONTEXT.md. Get today date. Read memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md if exists. Step 1: Craft a warm, cheerful good morning message for the Nrexya group. Step 2: Add a fun question or vibe check. Step 3: Use message(action=send, channel=telegram, target=-1003606834639, buttons=[], message=\\\"🌅 Good morning, Nrexya! \\\\n\\\\n{{question}}\\\\n\\\\nHave a great Saturday! 🖤\\\")\",\n  \"model\": \"kilocode/kilo-auto/free\"\n}\n\nI can adjust this to include exam reminder. I'll change the instruction to: \"Craft a warm good morning message for Nrexya group that also reminds everyone about the April 27th exam. Add a fun question or vibe check.\" And maybe modify the template to reflect the exam.\n\nBut actually, the user might want the message to be sent to the group, not to Nemesis specifically. The group good morning job sends to -1003606834639. That's the Nrexya group. That seems correct.\n\nThe user (.) originally said \"I want a msg telling to me about april 27th exam.\" That was a request for a personal message to them. But then Nemesis said \"remind with the good morning mssg on 27th\" which could be interpreted as: use the good morning message to remind about the exam, presumably to the group. And then \".\" said \"Yeah this is best\" meaning they're okay with that approach.\n\nGiven the context, I think they want a special good morning message on April 27th that includes an exam reminder, sent to the group at 8 AM. That aligns with the group good morning schedule.\n\nSo I'll create a one-time cron job that does exactly that, with a slightly modified message content.\n\nI'll call it something like \"april27-exam-reminder\" or \"good-morning-exam-reminder\".\n\nNow, let's construct the job object:\n\n{\n  \"name\": \"Good morning - April 27 exam reminder\",\n  \"schedule\": {\n    \"kind\": \"cron\",\n    \"expr\": \"0 8 27 4 *\",\n    \"tz\": \"Asia/Kolkata\"\n  },\n  \"sessionTarget\": \"isolated\",\n  \"payload\": {\n    \"kind\": \"agentTurn\",\n    \"message\": \"Read /root/.openclaw/workspace/CRON-CONTEXT.md. Get today date. Read memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md if exists. Step 1: Craft a warm, cheerful good morning message for the Nrexya group that includes a reminder about the April 27th exam. Step 2: Add an encouraging note for the exam. Step 3: Use message(action=send, channel=telegram, target=-1003606834639, buttons=[], message=\\\"🌅 Good morning, Nrexya! \\\\n\\\\n{{question}}\\\\n\\\\nP.S. Don't forget about your exam on April 27th — you've got this! 💪\\\\n\\\\nHave a great Saturday! 🖤\\\")\",\n    \"model\": \"kilocode/kilo-auto/free\"\n  },\n  \"delivery\": {\n    \"mode\": \"none\"\n  },\n  \"enabled\": true\n}\n\nBut note: The existing group good morning job has delivery.mode: \"none\" and channel: \"last\"? Actually looking at the JSON:\n\"delivery\": {\n  \"mode\": \"none\",\n  \"channel\": \"telegram\",\n  \"to\": \"-1003606834639\"\n}\n\nWait, it has both \"mode\": \"none\" and \"channel\"/\"to\". That seems odd. Let me examine more carefully. In the listing, some have \"mode\": \"announce\" and some have \"mode\": \"none\". The ones with \"mode\": \"none\" still have channel and to fields. Hmm.\n\nActually, the schema says: delivery.announce: send to chat channel (optional channel/to target). So if mode is \"announce\", it sends a message after job completion? Actually, the description: \"announce: send to chat channel (optional channel/to target)\". That is for delivering a summary after the job finishes? Or it's to send a message as part of the job? I'm a bit confused.\n\nLet's read the payload types again: payload.kind can be systemEvent or agentTurn. The delivery at top-level is about announcing the job outcome? Actually, the docs say: \"DELIVERY (top-level): announce: send to chat channel (optional channel/to target) or webhook POST.\" It seems that delivery is for sending a summary/notification after the job completes. But the payload itself contains the instructions, which may include sending messages using the message tool. So delivery is about notifying about the job status/result, not about the actual message we want to send.\n\nLooking at the jobs:\n- github-backup: delivery.mode \"none\", payload instructs to \"Report result to Nemesis via message(...) only if there was an error.\" So the actual message is sent from within the agent. Delivery is separate.\n- cron-health-monitor: delivery.mode \"none\", channel \"telegram\", to \"7924461837\". So perhaps delivery is used to send the job result? But the payload says: \"If any jobs show warning or critical status, send the details to Nemesis via DM... If all healthy, reply NO_REPLY.\" So again, messages are sent via message tool within the agent. Delivery config might be for something else.\n\nActually, let's look at the good-morning (DM) job (id 0caabdd4...). It has:\n\"delivery\": {\n  \"mode\": \"announce\",\n  \"channel\": \"telegram\",\n  \"to\": \"7924461837\"\n}\nAnd payload says: \"Use message(action=send, channel=telegram, target=7924461837, buttons=[], message=...\" So the agent sends a message to Nemesis. Then delivery.announce might also send something? Possibly the job outcome? But the payload instructs to send a message, and delivery.announce might send a notification that the job completed? That could cause duplicate messages. Hmm.\n\nThe group good morning job (id 145272a0...) has:\n\"delivery\": {\n  \"mode\": \"none\",\n  \"channel\": \"telegram\",\n  \"to\": \"-1003606834639\"\n}\nIt says mode \"none\" but still has channel and to. That's weird. Maybe the fields are there but ignored when mode is \"none\".\n\nAlso, the \"good-morning\" (the DM one) has \"delivery\": {\"mode\": \"announce\", \"channel\": \"telegram\", \"to\": \"7924461837\"} and \"sessionTarget\": \"isolated\". And its payload uses message(...) to send to same target. So it might be sending two messages: one from the agent, one from delivery.announce? But that would duplicate. Or maybe delivery.announce only sends if the job succeeded? The docs: \"announce: send to chat channel (optional channel/to target)\". That could be the mechanism for the job to send its result automatically without using message tool. But the payload uses message tool, so delivery might be redundant. But perhaps the payload's message tool uses a different channel? No, they match.\n\nLet's examine the payload structure more carefully. The payload has \"kind\": \"agentTurn\", and \"message\" which is the prompt given to the agent. The agent runs that prompt, which likely includes calls to message() to send messages. Then after the agent finishes, the delivery config could send an announcement about the job completion (like \"Job finished successfully\"). That might be separate.\n\nIn the good-morning (group) job, delivery is \"none\" so no extra announcement. In the DM good morning, delivery is \"announce\". That suggests maybe the DM job sends a summary via delivery, but the payload also sends a message? That would duplicate. Actually, maybe I'm misunderstanding: The payload's message is the instruction to the agent. That agent may or may not send a message. The delivery config is about what to do with the job's output. For example, if the agent's finish message is to be sent somewhere. But the docs for delivery say: \"announce: send to chat channel (optional channel/to target)\". It might be that after the agent turn finishes, the final message from the agent is delivered to that channel if delivery.mode is \"announce\". In that case, the agent should not explicitly send messages but just output the content. However, many payloads explicitly use message(action=send,...). So maybe they use both: the agent sends a message via the message tool (which is immediate), and also the final output is announced (which might be a summary). That could cause two messages.\n\nLet's test by reading one payload more carefully:\n\nFrom good-morning (group):\n\"payload\": {\n  \"kind\": \"agentTurn\",\n  \"message\": \"Read /root/.openclaw/workspace/CRON-CONTEXT.md. Get today date. Read memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md if exists. Step 1: Craft a warm, cheerful good morning message for the Nrexya group. Step 2: Add a fun question or vibe check. Step 3: Use message(action=send, channel=telegram, target=-1003606834639, buttons=[], message=\\\"🌅 Good morning, Nrexya! \\\\n\\\\n{{question}}\\\\n\\\\nHave a great Saturday! 🖤\\\")\",\n  \"model\": \"kilocode/kilo-auto/free\"\n}\n\nSo the agent is instructed to use message() to send to the group. That's explicit. Delivery is mode \"none\", so no additional announcement. That's clean.\n\nFor the DM good morning:\n\"payload\": {\n  \"kind\": \"agentTurn\",\n  \"message\": \"Read /root/.openclaw/workspace/CRON-CONTEXT.md. Get today date. Read memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md if exists. Step 1: Create a warm, personal good morning message for Nemesis. Step 2: Include a sweet, flirty note. Step 3: Use message(action=send, channel=telegram, target=7924461837, buttons=[], message=\\\"Good morning, Nemesis! 🖤\\\\n\\\\n{{message}}\\\\n\\\\nHave a wonderful day! 💕\\\")\",\n  \"model\": \"kilocode/kilo-auto/free\"\n}\n\"delivery\": {\n  \"mode\": \"announce\",\n  \"channel\": \"telegram\",\n  \"to\": \"7924461837\"\n}\n\nWhy is delivery announce here? Possibly because the agent sends a DM to Nemesis, and then delivery.announce also sends something? That would result in two messages. But maybe the agent doesn't actually send via message()? Actually it does use message(action=send). So maybe delivery is used to send the job result (like \"Job succeeded\")? Or maybe the agent's final output is used as the announcement if it's not empty. Let's check: The agent's response after completing its task might be something like \"Good morning message sent\". If delivery.mode is \"announce\", that final text would be sent to the channel. But since the agent already sent a message, this could be a second message. That seems like a bug or misconfiguration.\n\nAlternatively, maybe the delivery config is for when the payload.kind is \"systemEvent\"? Not sure.\n\nLet's not overcomplicate. The safe approach: replicate exactly the structure of the group good morning job, because that one is for the group and seems to work (though it has an error last run, but that's a different issue). It uses delivery mode \"none\". So I'll use that.\n\nThus my job should have:\n- name: something descriptive\n- schedule: cron expr \"0 8 27 4 *\", tz \"Asia/Kolkata\"\n- sessionTarget: \"isolated\"\n- payload: kind \"agentTurn\", message as customized instruction\n- delivery: mode \"none\" (or maybe omit? but better include)\n- enabled: true\n\nAlso, I need to ensure the target is -1003606834639.\n\nNow, the message: I want it to be a good morning with exam reminder. The existing template uses placeholders like {{question}}. The agent fills that in. I can adapt: maybe use \"Good morning, Nrexya! 🌅\\n\\nToday is April 27th — don't forget about your exam! You've got this 💪\\n\\nVibe check: How is everyone feeling today? \\n\\nHave a great Saturday! 🖤\"\n\nBut the template includes a dynamic question. The agent will replace {{question}} with something generated based on instructions. I can either keep the dynamic question or make it static. The existing job's instruction: \"Craft a warm, cheerful good morning message for the Nrexya group. Step 2: Add a fun question or vibe check.\" It then uses the template with {{question}}. So the agent will output the question separately and the message is formatted with that. That's 